Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses known to cause symptoms ranging from a common cold to more severe diseases, such as the severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) and the Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS). The severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus (SARS-CoV) caused a SARS outbreak in China in 2002 (
 Drosten 
  et al ., 2003
 ; 
 Ksiazek 
  et al ., 2003
 ), and MERS coronavirus (MERS-CoV) was the pathogen responsible for severe respiratory disease outbreaks in the Middle East in 2012 (
 Zaki 
  et al ., 2012
 ). SARS-CoV-2 is the seventh identified member of the family of coronaviruses which infect humans, and the main symptoms including fever, cough and fatigue are similar to those following SARS-CoV and MERS-CoV infection (
 Liu 
  et al ., 2020 a
 ).
